name: 3,4-dimethyl-cis-2-pentene
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: 3,4-dimethyl-cis-2-pentene has a melting point that we can predict by considering its structural components. Starting with the basic unit of cis-2-pentene, which has a melting point of -109.4°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The methyl groups can raise the melting point by approximately +10°C due to increased molecular weight and rigidity. The dimethyl substitution also introduces additional rigidity and molecular weight, which may contribute approximately +20°C. The cis-configuration can also contribute to the melting point due to the increased molecular rigidity, estimated at around +10°C.
